ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we synthesize I-CDs with bright green FL by the hydrothermal treatment of 3-aminobenzoborate acid (APBA), iohexol, and ethanediamine (EDA) (

                     Scheme 1
                     ). The obtained I-CDs show good water solubility and photobleaching resistance, exhibiting a rapid response to ClO−. In the presence of ClO−, the green FL of I-CDs can be efficiently quenched, with a linear range of 1 − 60 μM and the detection limit of 95.1 nM. The quenching mechanism is proven to be attributed to the structure destruction of I-CDs caused by oxidation of iodine by ClO−. Importantly, the I-CDs can be used for in situ measurement of ClO− level in living cells.

I-CDs with bright green FL are synthesized by the hydrothermal treatment of APBA, iohexol, and EDA. Among them, iohexol provides reducing iodine sites for ClO− recognition and EDA can serve as a nitrogen source to enhance the quantum efficiency of I-CDs. The boronic acid group of APBA can undergo dehydration condensation with the hydroxyl groups of iohexol, promoting the crosslinking polymerization of I-CDs through the covalent reaction. The results from thin-layer chromatographic separation analysis show that unlike the precursors, I-CDs have not a tail (
                        Fig. S1
                        ), indicating a relatively high purity of I-CDs by the purification strategy used.

The structure and composition of I-CDs are further analyzed through XPS and FT-IR spectra. The obtained I-CDs are composed of carbon (63.52 at%), nitrogen (13.27 at%), oxygen (23.11 at%), and iodine (0.1 at%) (
                        Fig. 1
                        e and Table S1
                        ). High-resolution C1s spectrum (
                        Fig. S5a
                        ) shows that I-CDs contain CO, C−N, C−O, and C−C bonds. High-resolution O1s spectrum (
                        Fig. S5b
                        ) further exhibits that CO and C−O bonds exist in I-CDs. Moreover, the C−N bond also has been found in high-resolution N1s spectrum (
                        Fig. S5c
                        ). Meanwhile, FT-IR spectrum (
                        Fig. 1
                        f) further confirms the existence of N−H/O−H (3354 cm−1), CO (1635 cm−1), and C−N (1380 cm−1) in I-CDs. In addition, the FT-IR spectrum of I-CDs is significantly different from that of the precursors, indicating the crosslinking polymerization of the precursors during the formation of I-CDs.

It is found that ClO− can efficiently quench the green FL of I-CDs (
                        Fig. S7
                        ), with a fast response time (
                        Fig. S8
                        ). To better quantify the ClO−, sensitivity analysis of the I-CDs is performed. The FL intensity of I-CDs in the presence of ClO− solution with different concentrations (1 − 100 μM) is tested. As shown in Fig. S9, the FL intensity of I-CDs gradually decreases as the concentration of ClO− increases from 0 to 100 μM, demonstrating the effective quenching of I-CDs FL by ClO−. The linear relationship between the difference in FL intensity (F0-F) at 512 nm and the concentration of ClO− is shown in Fig. 2
                        d. The F0-F value of the I-CDs is linearly correlated with the concentration of ClO− in the range of 1 – 60 µM, with a low limit of detection (LOD) of about 95.1 nM (3σ/K).

Meanwhile, the response mechanism of I-CDs to ClO− has been studied. From the 
                        Fig. 3
                        a, it can be observed that the characteristic absorption peak of the I-CDs has undergone a significant change before and after the addition of ClO−, shifting from 229 to 292 nm, indicating a great change in I-CDs structure. Meanwhile, no change of the lifetime for I-CDs before and after adding ClO− 
                        (
                        Fig. S10
                        ) indicates that no electron or energy transfer process occurs between I-CDs and ClO− because the presence of electron or energy transfer will cause changes in FL lifetime [30,31]. Furthermore, after the treatment of ClO−, the oxygen content of I-CDs significantly increases from 23.11 at% to 40.21 at%, while the iodine content obviously decreases from 0.1 at% to 0.05 at% (
                        Fig. 3
                        b and Table S1
                        ). Moreover, the oxidation effect of ClO− causes a significant decrease in zeta potential of I-CDs from −17.8 eV to −7.4 eV (
                        Fig. S11
                        ). Meanwhile, we further observe the Tyndall effect of I-CDs solution before and after the addition of ClO−. Results (
                        Fig. S12
                        ) show that there is a bright pathway in I-CDs solution when laser irradiation, showing an obvious Tyndall effect because of the nanoscale of I-CDs. However, upon the addition of ClO−, the Tyndall effect has significantly weakened, strongly suggesting the oxidative destruction of I-CDs structure by ClO−. The above results strongly reveal that ClO− can oxidize iodine with reducing properties, leading to the destruction of I-CDs structure and subsequent FL quenching.
